Experts need managers.
What does [Drucker] mean by "[experts] need [managers]"?
In particular, what is the role of the "manager" in this case?

[Essential Edition Management], p. 125, as explained in "Professional Issues.
>The biggest problem for professionals is to link their own knowledge and abilities to the overall outcome. Communication is a problem for experts. As long as one's output does not become the input of others, no results can be achieved. The output of experts is knowledge and information. Those who should use the output of experts must understand what they are trying to say and do. Experts tend to use jargon. They cannot speak without jargon. However, they are effective only when they are understood. They must supply what their customers, their colleagues in the organization, need.
> It is the manager's job to make professionals aware of this.